Reuters Corpus NLP Models Comparison¶

a simple from start to finish text mining project by Ilai Bachrach.

Created a one distributional space by counting and filtering the surface co-occurrences in a symmetric 5 word collocations span from the following corpus:

  • A lemmatized version of the Reuters corpus (the choice of the lemmatizer is up to you). For this step, you might need a PoS-tagger: you are welcome to choose one yourself. In case you can't do PoS tagging on your own, you can use the following command to load the provided corpus in data/reuters.pos (uploaded as a .zip file, so first unzip it):
with open("data/reuters.pos", "rb") as corpus_file:
    reuter_PoSTagged = pickle.load(corpus_file)

Remember to make motivated choices for the different strategies in building word vectors as described in class. Be explicit about:

  1. what lemmas you want to describe (i.e., what will be your target vectors?);
  2. how you want to describe them (i.e., what will be your contexts?);
  3. what filtering strategy you are going to choose (i.e., what do you exclude?).

In what follows I will make use of large code sections from Giovanni Colavizza's Notebook's on Vector Semantics and Word Embeddings

Source: https://github.com/Giovanni1085/AUC_TMCI_2021/tree/main/notebooks

  1. My target vectors will be Nouns from the reuters corpus
  2. The context will be co-occuring words in a symmetric window of 5 words around my target word
  3. Stopwords, non-alphabetic and words with length < 3 will be filtered out.
In [2]:
from nltk.corpus import wordnet as wn
from nltk.corpus import reuters
import string
import nltk
from collections import Counter

text = reuters.sents() #reading text into list of sentences
text_pos = [nltk.pos_tag(word, tagset = "universal") for word in text] #making pos-tagged words


finallistofwords = [] #filtering words into final list of words
x = set(string.punctuation) 
stopwords = nltk.corpus.stopwords.words('english')

for sentence in text_pos:
    z = []
    for i in sentence:
        if ((i[0].isalpha() and len(i[0]) > 3) and (not i[0] in stopwords)) :
            z.append((i[0].lower(), i[1]))
    finallistofwords.append(z)

#The tokenization did not catch words like U.S. as such I decide to remove words with len < 3 

mapping = {"VERB" : wn.VERB, "NOUN" : wn.NOUN, "ADJ" : wn.ADJ, "ADV" : wn.ADV}

reuters_lemmatized = []

for sentence in finallistofwords: #create a lemmatized list of all tokens.
    lemmatized_sentence = []
    for w, p in sentence:
        if p in [".", "X"]: #double-check to make sure to ignore odd occurences
            continue
        elif p in mapping.keys():
            lemma = nltk.WordNetLemmatizer().lemmatize(w, pos = mapping[p])
        else:
            lemma = nltk.WordNetLemmatizer().lemmatize(w)
        lemmatized_sentence.append("-".join([lemma, p]))
        
    reuters_lemmatized.append(lemmatized_sentence) 
    #since reuters lemma were filtered from the start, I will continue to use this here.

from itertools import chain
reuters_lemmas_frequencies = Counter(chain(*reuters_lemmatized))
print(reuters_lemmas_frequencies.items())

spansize = 5
surface_cs = Counter()

for sentence in reuters_lemmatized: 
    for i,w in enumerate(sentence):
        if w.split("-")[- 1] == "NOUN": #check symmetric span around target vector
            span_range = list(range(max(i - spansize, 0), i))
            span_range.extend(range(i + 1, min(i + spansize + 1, len(sentence))))
            for cw in [sentence[idx] for idx in span_range]:
                if w != cw: #exclude co-occurences with the same word
                    surface_cs[(w, cw)] += 1

print(surface_cs.most_common(15))

Vector representations¶

Weight the counts in the space you created for the previous question by using the following association measures on both spaces:

  1. One measure of your choice among those available in the nltk.BigramAssocMeasures module.
  2. The Positive Local Mutual Information measure (as shown in class/lab).
  3. I also used the smoothed ppmi measure proposed by Levy et al. (2015). Recall that the authors proposed to smooth the ppmi by raising the context counts to the power of $\alpha$ (where $\alpha= 0.75$ is reported to work well). That is, if $V_c$ is the vocabulary of all the contexts in a given space and $f(c)$ is the context frequency, they proposed the following association measure:
$$PPMI_\alpha (w,c) = max \left(0, \ log_2 \left(\frac{p(w,c)}{p(w) \cdot p_\alpha(c)}\right) \right) $$
In [36]:
from math import log
from nltk.metrics import BigramAssocMeasures as bam
In [37]:
N = sum(surface_cs.values())

def ppmi(o_11, r_1, c_1, n): 
    
    """
    Positive Pointwise Mutual Information (Church & Hanks, 1990)
    
    """
    observed = o_11
    expected = (r_1*c_1)/n 
    res = log(observed/expected,2)
    return max(0, res)


def plmi(o_11, r_1, c_1, n):
    """
    Positive Local Mutual Information, useful for leveraging the 
    low-frequency bias of the PPMI
    """
    res = o_11 * ppmi(o_11, r_1, c_1, n)
    return res
In [38]:
def smooth_ppmi(o_11, r_1, c_1, n):
    
    
    """Source: https://web.stanford.edu/~jurafsky/slp3/slides/vector1.pdf"""
    
    observed = o_11
    probofc = c_1/n
    alph = 0.75
    palphac = (probofc**alph)/(probofc**alph+(1-probofc)**alph)
    
    expected = (r_1/n) * palphac
    res = log(observed/expected,2)
    return max(0, res)
$$p_\alpha(c) = \frac{number of(c)^\alpha}{sum_c number of(c)^\alpha}$$

where: $$p_\alpha(c) = \frac{p(c)^.75}{p(c)^.75+ (1-p(c))^.75}$$

bampmi_surface = Counter()

for i, x in filtered_cooccs_surface.items(): #creating counter object with weights for bam.pmi

    bampmi_surface[i] = bam.pmi(x, (reuters_lemmas_frequencies[i[0]], reuters_lemmas_frequencies[i[1]]), N)

print("BAM.PMI: ", bampmi_surface.most_common(10)) #measure of my choice

for i, x in filtered_cooccs_surface.items(): #creating counter object with weights for plmi

    plmis_surface[i] = plmi(x, reuters_lemmas_frequencies[i[0]], reuters_lemmas_frequencies[i[1]], N)

# lemma to row/column index mappings
sorted_vectors = sorted(selected_reuters_noun_frequencies)
vectors_indices = dict((v,i) for i,v in enumerate(sorted_vectors))
contexts_indices = dict((v,i) for i,v in enumerate(sorted(filtered_reuters_lemmas_frequencies))) #2
#frequencies of each word, 
# initialize my selected BAM.pmi-Weighted matrix
bampmiMat = np.zeros((len(vectors_indices), len(contexts_indices)))

# populate the matrix
for pair, weight in bampmi_surface.items():
    bampmiMat[vectors_indices[pair[0]]][contexts_indices[pair[1]]] = weight

# initialize the PLMI-Weighted matrix
plmiMat = np.zeros((len(vectors_indices), len(contexts_indices)))

# populate the matrix
for pair, weight in plmis_surface.items():
    plmiMat[vectors_indices[pair[0]]][contexts_indices[pair[1]]] = weight
    
# initialize the smoothedPPMI-Weighted matrix
smoothedppmiMat = np.zeros((len(vectors_indices), len(contexts_indices)))

# populate the matrix
for pair, weight in smoothppmi_surface.items():
    smoothedppmiMat[vectors_indices[pair[0]]][contexts_indices[pair[1]]] = weight
    
dimensions = 100

# I select the ARPACK wrapper which using SVD transforms my original 8k+ dimensions into 100

bam_pmiMat_tr100 = sklearn.decomposition.TruncatedSVD(n_components = dimensions, algorithm = "arpack").fit_transform(bampmiMat)
plmiMat_tr100 = sklearn.decomposition.TruncatedSVD(n_components = dimensions, algorithm = "arpack").fit_transform(plmiMat)
smoothedppmiMat_tr100 = sklearn.decomposition.TruncatedSVD(n_components = dimensions, algorithm = "arpack").fit_transform(smoothedppmiMat)

U, s, Vt = linalg.svd(plmiMat)  

# Ignoring Vt

rel_variance = ( s**2 / sum(s**2) ) * 100
y_values = rel_variance
x_values = np.arange(len(y_values))

plt.plot(x_values, y_values, linestyle = '-')

plt.xlabel("Singular Values", labelpad = 20)
plt.ylabel("Relative Variance (%)", labelpad = 10)

plt.show()

    'size': 100, # for now I will be using 100 dimensions of embeddings as I want to fairly compare it with my other models
    'window': 5, # window -/+ before and after focus word as in question 1
    'iter': 5, # number of iterations over the corpus
    'min_count': 5, # filter on words whose frequency is below this count
    'sg': 1, #I tried both CBOW and SG and found the SG to report better results.
    'negative': 5, # no changes.
    'workers': 4, # no changes.
    'alpha': 0.12 # initial learning rate for SGD. I saw that I could tweak it to perform better on the test. It still performs well with alpha of 0.05.

#training my own model

from gensim.models import Word2Vec
from gensim.models import KeyedVectors
import gensim.downloader as api

model1 = api.load("glove-wiki-gigaword-100") #load original
model1.save_word2vec_format('gwg100.txt', binary=False) #save in txt format

model2 = Word2Vec(size=100, min_count=1)
model2.build_vocab(listofsentences) #build with original sentences
total_examples = model2.corpus_count

model2.build_vocab([list(model1.vocab.keys())], update=True) #build with vocab from model1
model2.intersect_word2vec_format('gwg100.txt', binary=False, lockf=1.0) #intersecting the two vocabs
model2.train(listofsentences, total_examples=total_examples, epochs=model2.iter)

print(model2)

Evaluating on semantic similarity¶

Evaluate the performance of your models on a semantic similarity task. Using SimLex-999 as gold standard. Evaluate all of your models on the dataset in data/SimLex-999.txt, and determine the best performing model. Note: There should be 5 to 8 model evaluations in total. 5 if you did not do any extra (2 from 4.1 + 2 from 4.2 + 1 from 4.3), and 8 if you did them all (3 from 4.1 + 3 from 4.2 + 2 from 4.3).

  1. Your evaluation should follow the approach shown in lab 4 (Section 1.6: "Evaluating your Model"), using a correlation measure on model predictions and the (human) gold standard.
  2. Remember to visualize your results (e.g., as bar plots).
  3. Take note (and report) the overlap between your models and the SimLex-999 dataset, i.e., how many pairs are shared by your model and the evaluation dataset.
  4. Make sure to discuss your results and provide your reasoning on them.

Remarks¶

  • The 'SimLex-999' dataset is described in data/SimLex-999.README.txt, and the author's github page. Hint: the relevant judgements are those in the SimLex999 column.
  • To directly compare the models against the gold standard, you will have to find the overlap between them, i.e. the pairs that occur in your model and the evaluation dataset.

I begin my evaluation against a dictionary of nouns that overlap in both my vectors_indices and SimLex-999

In [49]:
makinglists = []
for w, i in vectors_indices.items():
    makinglists.append(w.split("-")[0]) #making liss of only nouns without pos tag

simLex_999 = dict()

with open("data/SimLex-999.txt") as f:
    contents = f.read().split("\n")
    listofitems = []
    
    for n, line in enumerate(contents):
        items = line.split("\t") 
        listofitems.append(items)
        if (listofitems[n][0] in makinglists and listofitems[n][1] in makinglists):
                w1 = items[0] + "-NOUN" #I chose to compare only nouns
                w2 = items[1] + "-NOUN" 
                simLex_999[(w1, w2)] = float(listofitems[n][4])

bam_pmiSimMat = sklearn.metrics.pairwise.cosine_similarity(bampmiMat)
plmiSimMat = sklearn.metrics.pairwise.cosine_similarity(plmiMat)
smoothppmiSimMat = sklearn.metrics.pairwise.cosine_similarity(smoothedppmiMat)

bam_pmitrunkSimMat = sklearn.metrics.pairwise.cosine_similarity(bam_pmiMat_tr100)
plmitrunkSimMat = sklearn.metrics.pairwise.cosine_similarity(plmiMat_tr100)
smoothppmitrunkSimMat = sklearn.metrics.pairwise.cosine_similarity(smoothedppmiMat_tr100)


measure2mat = {"BAM.PMI": bam_pmiSimMat, "positiveLMI": plmiSimMat, "BAM-tr100": bam_pmitrunkSimMat, 
               "plmi-tr100" : plmitrunkSimMat, "sppmi" : plmitrunkSimMat, "sppmi-tr100" : smoothppmitrunkSimMat}

rhos = []
measures = []

for m, mat in measure2mat.items():
    
    wordSim_ratings = []
    vsm_sims = []
    for (w1, w2), r in simLex_999.items():
        w1idx = vectors_indices[w1]
        w2idx = vectors_indices[w2]
        
        wordSim_ratings.append(r)
        vsm_sims.append(mat[w1idx, w2idx])
        
    rho, pval = scipy.stats.spearmanr(wordSim_ratings, vsm_sims)
    
    rhos.append(rho)
    print(m, rho)
    measures.append(m)

wordSim_ratings = []

counting = 0
for line in listofitems:
    if len(line) > 1:

        word2 = line[1]
        pos = line[2]
        value = line[3]

        if word1 in model.wv.vocab.keys() and word2 in model.wv.vocab.keys() and pos == "N":
            counting = counting + 1
            wordSim_ratings.append(float(value))
            vsm_sims.append(model.wv.similarity(word1, word2))

rhos.append(rho)
measures.append("word2vec")

It is explanable that PPMI and PLMI have a lower spearman score than PPMI and PLMI as they have lower dimensions, however, it seems off to me that PPMI is larger than PLMI as PLMI should add increased weighting to word-context pairs with higher frequency. Perhaps this has to do with the fact that this test is on nouns overlapping with initial vocab and not both word-context pairs.

On another note it seems off to me that the sppmi performs worse than bam.pmi as it should tackle PPMIs bias towards co- occurrences of rare words.

The Word2vec models clearly outperform the rest. Interestingly, whenever I re-run the notebook they perform differently, perhaps this is because the hidden layers create different weights everytime.

4. Discussion

Since there are very few overlaps in comparison to the total number of pairs in the model PPMI and PLMI perform poorly. The dimensionality reduced versions of PPMI and PLMI perform worse as they do not seem to contain as much information, that can aid the final similarity score from the space. As expected Word2Vec Performs very well in comparison to all models.

A word on filtering

Many of the word context pairs that my counter and the list in sim999 have in common appear very infrequently in the text, as such, using these pairs as a test against my word vectors will not produce very good results. This can be drawn back to when I remove infrequent word context pairs in question 1. When I implement this filter the number of common pairs reduces for my counter and sim999 reduces from 50 to 17. The dimensionality reduced version of the plmi and chosen bam perform better without removing infrequent word context pairs. This makes sense becasue chosing the right space early on will have immense performance differences.

Going further: testing the models with a dictionary of overlapping word context pairs

Because the PPMI overvalues low frequencies words it is performs much better than PLMI if I do not remove low frequency words at the start. With prefilterting word-context pairs of less than 10 freq and words with freq less than 10 for dice method and performing the test only on overlaps of word context pairs I receive the following values:
